<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="vr-design-patterns">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Design immersive VR experiences with comfort-first patterns: choose safe locomotion, anchor UI in world space, apply accessible fallbacks.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>vr</tag>
      <tag>immersive</tag>
      <tag>ux-design</tag>
      <tag>interaction-design</tag>
      <tag>comfort</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>spatial</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>VR Design Patterns</title>
    <summary>User-centered VR design starts with comfort: place a visible ground plane and stable horizon, choose teleportation-first locomotion for novices, anchor UI to the world (not the head), and provide accessibility fallbacks including seated modes, subtitles, and one-handed control.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Full VR lacks real-world context and can cause discomfort. Poorly designed VR experiences trigger motion sickness, simulator sickness, and presence loss. Ground planes, guardrails, and wrist-anchored UI prevent nausea. Safe default locomotion (teleportation over smooth movement) ships fewer tickets. Accessible fallbacks (seated mode, hand-tracking + controller choice, subtitles) expand addressable market and build trust.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Fully-immersive Quest, Vision Pro, Pico, Index, Vive deployments.</item>
        <item>Designing locomotion, in-VR menus, hand-tracking interactions, or seated/room-scale modes.</item>
        <item>Migrating a 2D enterprise tool (training, collaboration, design review) to a VR-native experience.</item>
        <item>Specifying comfort defaults and accessibility fallbacks for a VR build.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>AR / passthrough / MR-first apps — use ar-design-patterns and immersive-design-principles instead.</item>
        <item>360° video viewers without interaction — patterns over-engineer the experience.</item>
        <item>Web-based WebXR demos with less than 2 minutes target session — most patterns assume sustained presence.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="VR Environment Design">
      <rule>
        <statement>Ground plane MUST be always visible and clearly differentiated from walls/ceiling (e.g., via color, grid, or texture).</statement>
        <rationale>Ground plane is the anchor for spatial orientation. Floating in featureless space causes disorientation and motion sickness.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Horizon MUST be stable and at expected position; never tilt camera or horizon unexpectedly.</statement>
        <rationale>Mismatch between expected and actual horizon triggers balance system and inner-ear discomfort.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Scale MUST be either human-scale or clearly and consistently different (e.g., giant or miniature). Never ambiguous scaling.</statement>
        <rationale>Ambiguous scale breaks presence and triggers cognitive load.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Lighting MUST be consistent and comfortable; avoid sudden flashes, strobing, or extreme contrast.</statement>
        <rationale>Discomfort and accessibility (photosensitivity, motion sensitivity).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Guardian/chaperone boundary MUST be visible during locomotion and clearly marked.</statement>
        <rationale>Users need to know playspace limits to avoid real-world collision.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Locomotion Methods">
      <rule>
        <statement>Default locomotion MUST be teleportation or room-scale walking for novices. Smooth controller movement is opt-in only.</statement>
        <rationale>Smooth locomotion causes motion sickness in 30-40% of users on first exposure. Teleport is perceived as safer and includes no risk.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Comfort-First Locomotion Defaults">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Novice user: teleport (with optional 30° or 45° snap-turn)
Experienced user: opt-in smooth locomotion with comfort vignette
Room-scale: walking only, no movement beyond Guardian
Seated: vehicle or seated perspective; no locomotion input needed
Flying: allow only in sandbox/creative tasks, not exploration/navigation]]></code>
        <note>Pin device in prompt: Quest 3 vs. Vision Pro vs. Pico have different hand-tracking capabilities.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Smooth controller movement as default for "natural feel".</description>
        <reason>Causes motion sickness in novices; ships high churn and refund rates. Force teleport-first even if it feels outdated.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="UI in VR">
      <rule>
        <statement>UI panels MUST float in world space or attach to hand/wrist, NEVER to head.</statement>
        <rationale>Head-locked UI moves with eye rotation, triggering vestibular mismatch and nausea. World-space UI stays stable and allows gaze-and-point selection.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Primary UI MUST anchor to wrist, world-panel, or controller within 1.5 m of user. Further = illegible or unreachable.</statement>
        <rationale>Ergonomics and reachability within arm span and focal distance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Selection MUST use gaze + confirm (hand pinch, button press) or direct touch (for seated). Never gaze-only (accidental selection).</statement>
        <rationale>Prevents accidental interaction and respects user intent.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Spatial audio MUST provide feedback for interaction: button hover, selection, state change.</statement>
        <rationale>Audio cues reduce visual UI clutter, improve presence, and aid accessibility (blind users, busy hands).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad" title="Nausea-Inducing UI Anchoring">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Menu locked to head HUD
Floating button 3 m away in dark void
Selection without confirmation (gaze triggers action)
No audio feedback; visual-only cues
Flashing/spinning UI elements]]></code>
        <note>All of these increase motion sickness and decrease usability.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Accessibility and Fallbacks">
      <rule>
        <statement>Supported input methods MUST include both controller rays and hand-tracking (with graceful fallback). One-handed mode is mandatory.</statement>
        <rationale>Inclusivity: users with single-limb disability, fatigue, or reduced dexterity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Supported pose modes MUST include seated and standing; recenter must be one-button accessible at all times.</statement>
        <rationale>Health and accessibility: users with balance disorders, mobility aids, limited space.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Accessibility fallbacks MUST include: subtitles, captions, color-blind-friendly UI (not red/green alone), high-contrast mode.</statement>
        <rationale>Deaf users, color-blind users, low-vision users.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Reduce-motion accessibility setting MUST disable auto-transitions, smooth camera pans, and particle effects.</statement>
        <rationale>Photosensitivity, vestibular disorders, motion sensitivity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Ship a 2D fallback build (flat screen, mouse + keyboard, or mobile). VR-only excludes marketing screenshots, accessibility users, and ~15% of buyers.</statement>
        <rationale>Revenue and market reach.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Onboarding and Orientation">
      <rule>
        <statement>First-time-user orientation MUST be under 60 seconds. Longer onboarding is abandoned or skipped.</statement>
        <rationale>Attention and presence decay in immersive environments.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Comfort vignette (optional darkening of peripheral vision during locomotion) MUST be toggleable and tunable in magnitude and fade-in time.</statement>
        <rationale>Reduces motion sickness in smooth locomotion; some users prefer it off.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Performance and Validation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Frame rate MUST be sustained at device-minimum: 72 Hz Quest 2, 90 Hz Quest 3, 120 Hz Vision Pro. No drops below minimum.</statement>
        <rationale>Frame drops trigger motion sickness and presence loss.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Frame-budget estimates from LLMs require on-device validation. Do not ship based on agent-estimated draw calls or fillrate.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs cannot model platform-specific CPU/GPU constraints accurately.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pattern selection requires in-headset verification with at least 5 testers including one prone to motion sickness.</statement>
        <rationale>Motion sickness is highly individual; laboratory testing is necessary.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>Use agents to map interaction requirements to known VR patterns (locomotion choice, menu placement, comfort vignette, selection method) and to generate playtest scripts.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Agent Workflow for VR Pattern Selection">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Recommended subagents:
- faion-ux-researcher-agent: produces presence/immersion questionnaires (IPQ, SSQ, PQ), recruits VR-novice + expert mix
- faion-usability-agent: heuristic evaluation against Oculus VRCs and Apple visionOS HIG

Prompt pattern:
Recommend VR design patterns for:
  task: <task description>
  duration: <minutes>
  device: Quest3|VisionPro|Pico4|Index
  pose: seated|standing|room-scale
  user_familiarity: novice|intermediate|expert

Output JSON:
  locomotion: {method, justification, comfort_score}
  ui_placement: {anchor, hand_attached|world|wrist}
  selection: gaze+pinch|controller_ray|direct_touch|voice
  comfort: {vignette, snap_turn_deg, frame_rate_min}
  fallbacks: [accessibility_fallback per interaction]
Cite Oculus VRC or Apple HIG section per recommendation]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Known Limitations">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Locomotion comfort is assumed universal ("teleport works for everyone").</description>
        <reason>Teleport comfort varies wildly by individual; some users prefer smooth movement. Individual playtesting is mandatory.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Floating UI panels assumed to follow ergonomics like real-world objects.</description>
        <reason>Wrist fatigue rises after ~8 min of pinch input. Sim physics differ from human ergonomics; limit pinch-intensive tasks to &lt;5 min or offer voice/controller alternative.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Guardian/chaperone boundary treated as device-agnostic.</description>
        <reason>Meta, SteamVR, and visionOS have different APIs and visual markers. Specify SDK version in prompt and test on each platform.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hand-tracking jitter ignored; assumes precise selection under low light.</description>
        <reason>Hand-tracking fails under low light or outdoor bright sunlight. Always provide controller fallback.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Eye-tracking gaze-and-confirm treated as portable across platforms.</description>
        <reason>visionOS supports eye-tracking natively; Quest 3 standard doesn't. Pin device.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Comfort vignette parameters applied as agent defaults without playtest tuning.</description>
        <reason>Vignette size, fade-in time, and persistence vary by user comfort tolerance. Defaults are conservative-to-broken.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="References">
      <list>
        <item>Apple, visionOS Human Interface Guidelines — Immersive Experiences. https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/immersive-experiences</item>
        <item>Meta, Oculus VRC for Quest. https://developer.oculus.com/resources/bp-vrc-quest/</item>
        <item>Jerald, The VR Book (2015).</item>
        <item>LaViola et al., 3D User Interfaces: Theory and Practice (2nd ed., 2017).</item>
        <item>Bowman et al., 3D User Interfaces: Theory and Practice — companion empirical studies on locomotion.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <see-also>
